{
  "answer": "**Death (marg).**\n\nThis line comes from the *maqta* (signature closing couplet) of the famous ghazal \"Aah ko chahiye ik umr asar hote tak\" (ch. 3) in Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*:\n\n> Gham-e-hasti ka 'Asad' kis se ho juz marg ilaaj  \n> Shama har rang mein jalti hai seher hote tak[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:** The sorrow of existence—what remedy is there, Asad, except death? The candle burns in every hue until the dawn arrives.\n\n**Translation:** What cure for life's great sorrow, Asad, say? A candle burns in every way till morning's light.[^2]\n\nGhalib (using his *takhallus* Asad) poses this as a rhetorical question, declaring death as the sole remedy (*juz marg ilaaj*) for existence's pain (*gham-e-hasti*, often rendered as \"sorrow of life\" or \"sorrow of existence\"). The metaphor of the candle (*shama*) burning through the night underscores life's fleeting, consuming torment until its inevitable end at dawn.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 3: \"Aah ko chahiye ik umr asar hote tak\" ([transliteration](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/transliteration/#p-82d15b)).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 3: \"Aah ko chahiye ik umr asar hote tak\" ([translation](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/03-aah-ko-chahiye-ik-umr-asar-hote-tak/translation/#p-82d15b)).",
